<br>
When your family suffers long, it is not hard to become accustomed to the hardship.  Long before the mark’s true meaning was revealed to the Halasians, it meant isolation, rejection, and if you managed to survive, exile.  Her entire clan had been blessed with the mark after engaging Vox on a rescue mission.  For years, the Pinesent clan was ostracized.  A once proud and glorious family diminished into factions and then individuals.  Clan Pinesent scattered to the winds rather than face the troubles at home.  And those that stayed, either because of being too old or too young, were left to their own devices.  The only thing that remain intact for so long was the clan compound.  A large empty circle carved into the rock of the mountains that protected eight family homes and a communal banquet hall, it echoed in the wind, devoid of family cheer.<br>
<br>
Memories have a way of showing themselves on the face.  Urda had been bitter about her family’s treatment.  The eventual revelation of the mark’s meaning brought back some prosperity.  But there were still those who feared what they did not understand, and thus treated her clan with the same contempt and fear they always had.  It was dark by the hearth, the fire’s low burning embers casting a dark orange glow on her features.  Reaching out from underneath her fur blanket, Urda found her cup of tea sitting on the heart and brought it slowly to her mouth.<br>
<br>
The letter was from home.  Wora, her younger sister had been found living among the halflings in Rivervale.  She smiled at the thought of Wora, being the barbarian female that she was, towering over the halfling population.  She was one of the one’s who left long ago after Urda herself had gone out on a mission from The Tribunal.  And rather than continue the tradition of the shamanistic rites, Wora had opted to don the warrior’s mantle.  This made Urda smile.  Wora was tall to be sure.  But a muscled warrior?  Among the halflings?  It was a comical juxtaposition.<br>
<br>
She was saddened that there would not be another shaman after her in the clan.  But each had their own call to follow.  And hadn’t Urda herself once questioned the rightness of being made a shaman without formal consent?  The family’s downfall had left wiggle room inside of tradition.  No doubt Wora did what she had to to help the family prosper in any way they could.  There was no shame in that.<br>
<br>
The chair across her was empty.  But for a moment, Urda imagined Wora sitting there.  It had been so long since she had seen her.  She was a strange girl when she was younger.  Urda remembered how she used to always smell of woodchips.  She would bury herself in them by the carpenters hut and come out with chunks of the stuff in her hair.  Would she still smell like that?  The thought of Wora hanging out by a halfling carpenter’s shop made her chuckle.<br>
<br>
Urda continued sipping her tea as the embers continued their glow.  Yes, good news indeed, she thought.  Good news indeed.<br>
