<br>
Wora had apparently caught him in the latter.  With a few swift moves he had managed to completely unearth the barbarian and was ready to make sure she thought twice about coming back.<br>
<br>
“Aye. There ya are.  Looking stupid as per usual.  Never met a barbarian who wasn’t.”<br>
<br>
“Yee canna blame me Master Woodworker.  I have tried other carpenters.  No one gets them as fine and lovely as you do.  And besides,” Wora quickly added, “Limble uses that blasted alder wood.  Who would like the smell o’ that?” She tried winking at him, but Fipple just scowled at her. <br>
<br>
“Bina’s looking for you, you overgrown treewee.  Says she has something for you.  Get going before I set you to her full of holes.” He brandished his pitchfork convincingly enough that Wora backed off, but not without blowing him a kiss and smiling before she took off to see Bina.<br>
<br>
“I shoulda known that’s where you’d be,” Bina said as she watched Wora duck into the kitchen.  “Just look at you!” she plucked a few chips out of wra’s hair and then gave when she realized how many there were.  “The Brandil’s have been looking forward to that bed all week long.  Should have put two and two together…a messenger came bearing this my dear.”<br>
<br>
Bina handed Wora a scroll sealed with a symbol she had never seen before.  But one wiff told her where it came from.  She quickly opened it and scanned the contents.  She nearly burst from the volume of tears she was holding back.  She did not want Bina to see her explode like that.  It was from Urda!  <br>
<br>
“Such wonderful news…glad to hear…miss you terribly…have some fine mead, well of course she does…the mark of Veeshan…many friends…come as soon as you can…enclosed is….a key!”  a small pouch dropped into her lap as she read, containing a small brass key.  “And a map…Oh Bina!  My sister is alive!  And she wants me to join her!”<br>
<br>
“We always knew we would not be able to keep you long, dear one.” Bina looked sad but understanding.  “Your own clan is setting itself to right again, and it is time you joined them.  No no no, little one,” Bina always called her that as a sort of joke, “you must go.  But make sure to say your goodbyes to everyone first.  We want to be ableto welcome you back with open arms.”<br>
<br>
Wora bent down and hugged Bina as hard as she could without snapping her little ribs.  Bina had been her family since she arrived here and owed her a great deal.<br>
<br>
“I’ll be back soon enough, Bina,” Wora promised.  She started collecting things to take with her on her trip. But Bina had already left the house.  <br>
<br>
After all was collected and arranged, Wora gathered her things together and grabbed her sword.  It was time to go, but where was everyone?  She wandered through Rivervale trying to find people to bid farwell to, but everyone seemed to have vanished.  Disappointed and a little sad, Wora made her way to Misty Thicket.  She could not delay any longer if she was to make Kithicor Forest before nightfall.<br>
<br>
As she made her way to the tunnel leading out, she noticed one lone figure standing there waiting.  It was Fipple and he held in his hand something that looked like a pitchfork.  Great, Wora thought, wonderful way to send me off into the world, with a halfling bumblebee on my tail.<br>
<br>
But Fipple stood his ground.  His face was a study in forced passivity.  When Wora came close enough he held up his hand.<br>
<br>
“You’ve been a thorn in my side since the day you showed up here,” he began.  “You talk funny.  You dress funny.  And you drink too much.  Those little ‘constitutionals’ you like to take behind my woodshed disturb my privacy and showed your complete lack of respect for anyone but yourself.”<br>
<br>
Wora looked at the ground and shuffled her feet a bit.  This wasn’t the goodbye she was hoping for.  But she stayed and listened, determined to prove him wrong about her respect for him.<br>
<br>
“There hasn’t been a day that has gone by when I didn’t curse them that brought you into this world,”  Fipple sighed at this last statement.  “But you’ve also protected all of us from things too powerful for us to defend against on our own.  You have showed an inkling of decency on a few occasions and I would be a bad halfling if I didn’t at least acknowledge that you saved my butt on a few occasions,” he was frowning now, the admission of this was obviously unpleasant.<br>
<br>
“In return for that, I offer you this spear.  I crafted it myself with you in mind a few months ago.  Finished it as soon as I could.  Should allow you to take advantage of that blasted reach of yours.”  He handed her the spear gruffly, which she took in awe and gratitude.<br>
<br>
“And to keep you from inflicting yourself on any other undeserving soul, here you go,” and with that he handed Wora a pouch.  When she opened it, the sent of fresh woodchip wafted up to her nose and she closed her eyes and smelled it deeply.<br>
<br>
When she opened them again, Fipple was gone and the way to Misty Thicket was clear.  She said thank you to the air around her and strode forward.  Before leaving the city entirely, she decided to take one last look behind her.  <br>
<br>
There in the corridor stood every last resident of Rivervale.  No one waved.  No one said goodbye.  Fipple and Bina stood in front of them all and smiled.  Wora smiled back and nodded before she made her way to her sister.  Her long lost sister.  <br>
<br>
“Urda…listen to the wind…I am coming…”<br>
