</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=375D88><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/btearsofveeshan25764.showUserPublicProfile?gid=worapinesent>Wora Pinesent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/22/02 3:02:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ftearsofveeshan25764frm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=130.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: a letter from home</span><hr size=1> Common sense would of course dictate that when facing a path that, once the sun went down, teemed with powerful undead creatures who’s merest touch could kill you, you would opt to make camp away from said path.  Far away, if possible, and wait until daylight to cross it.  Common sense would not lead you down said path just as the sun was passing beneath the horizon.<br>
<br>
Of course, she knew no one named Common Sense.  And since camping now would delay her reunion with Urda, Wora opted to make a run for it.  She was sure she could outrun anything this forest threw at her.  Well almost sure.  But what could possibly happen?<br>
<br>
So it was very lucky when, after falling in battle with a large, red skeleton with its hand about to touch the area above her heart, that a blur of wolf knocked it off its feet, scattering its odd colored bones in every direction.<br>
<br>
“…huh?…oh!” said Wora as she realized what had just saved her.  She went to pet the animal only to have her hand run right through it.  The wolf spirit smiled its canine grin at her and sat down by her side while she tended her wounds.<br>
<br>
“You know…I had that creature right where I wanted it.” Wora said to the spirit.  She doubted it could understand much of what she said but she went on anyway.<br>
<br>
“Urda must be getting good if she can send a wolf all the way out to meet me.  Must still think I’m too young to travel.” She could have sworn the wolf just shrugged at her then.  Wora dismissed it and finished the last of her bandages.<br>
<br>
“Ok, I’m good to go wolfie.  Much oblidged and all.  I’m ok now.  Off you go!”  The wolf stayed by her side.  Wora wasn’t really surprised.  She sighed and continued walking.<br>
<br>
The rest of the forest walk went smoothly enough.  The wolf easily batted aside those few creatures that would do Wora harm.  He seemed to humor her toward the forest’s edge however, backing off a bit and letting her get that last few strikes in on a half crippled zombie.  When Wora gloated a bit, the wolf spirit merely sighed and trotted over to her side.<br>
<br>
It was now pitch dark, and Wora had to admit to even herself that she was tired.  Being on alert at all times was exhausting work.<br>
<br>
“Ok wolf.  Be really useful.  Find us a safe spot to camp.”  The wolf did a quick scan and walked over to a clearing behind a boulder and sat down.<br>
<br>
“Ah wonderful.  Ok.  Let’s see here…”  And with that, Wora began to make camp.  The starry night sky lulled her into dreams with their twinkling.  The moon of Luclin reminded her of the moon shaped cakes that she had grabbed from Bina’s kitchen.  She ate it and felt a small pang on longing.  She wasn’t sure when she would return to Rivervale again.  With that thought, the moon cake became that much sweeter, and she savored each bite with a small tear.<br>
<br>
The next part of her travels, she knew, would be tricky.  And she wished for the first time since leaving Rivervale, that she hadn’t come this far alone.  How was she going to find Urda without getting ripped to shreds?  Urda couldn’t have just come to Rivervale to fetch her?<br>
<br>
All young people think they are invincible.  But every so often they face things that they realize are bigger and more difficult than they ever imagined.  In a few cases, failure could mean death.  And that’s where Wora was now.  Failure could kill her before she got to Urda.<br>
<br>
To someone older, this would  not be that big a revelation. Clerics could resurrect lost souls.  But Wora knew no clerics who could come to her rescue.  She was alone for the first time in a long time, minus the wolf spirit, but for some reason the thought brought little comfort.  Tears began to flow down her cheeks.<br>
<br>
“Stupid sister.  Stupid me. Should have stayed in Rivervale.  And what are you looking at?” the wolf spirit was staring at her with a sad puppy expression.  “You can’t protect me from everything.  My family relied on your kind too much anyway.  Never saw the point.  Spirits….BAH!”  <br>
<br>
Wora kicked some dirt toward the fire, which effectively smothered about half of it.  Wora scowled.  Things were not as fun as she thought they would be.  She went to sleep hoping that tomorrow would provide some clarity.  And maybe some idea of how not to die a horrible death.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=375D88><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/btearsofveeshan25764.showUserPublicProfile?gid=worapinesent>Wora Pinesent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/26/02 2:36:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ftearsofveeshan25764frm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=130.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: a letter from home</span><hr size=1> Wora rose in the morning well chilled and covered in morning dew.  Urda’s pet was still by her side, looking off into the horizon.  When it heard her wake up, it turned and stood looking at her face with its puppy like smile.<br>
<br>
It took a while for Wora to realize where she was.  It had been years since she had woken up in a place other than Bina’s hut.  After reorienting herself and sighing with realization, she began rummaging through her packs to find another Bina cake for breakfast.  She had a long way to go yet and was certain that she would need to muster up her resolve in order to make it to her destination in a timely matter.<br>
<br>
The world of Norrath offered her many challenges.  Thankfully, Urda’s pooch kept to his duties and Wora begrudgingly thanked him on numerous occasions when he stepped in and fended off a creature that would have certainly meant her demise.  When she arrived at Freeport, a place that Urda had called a wretched stinkhole of humanity, Wora breathed a sigh of relief.  She dropped her bags in a corner and propped herself up against one of the towering stonewalls.  Wora looked around.  Sure it was dusty.  And the guards kept looking at her funny.  But at least she was out of reach of orcs, ogres, gnolls, the undead, giants, tigers, bears, snakes, drakes, and the occasional talking griffon.  How bad could this place be?<br>
<br>
The trip had exhausted her supplies, so Wora wandered into what looked like a local bar and sat down.  She was alone except for a small rat scurrying along the floor.  The bartender eyed her up and down and then poured a big stein full of mead.  Wora smiled.  That stein of mead was just what she needed.  So when the barkeep set the mug down on the floor, she frowned slightly.<br>
<br>
“I would rather serve the rat at my feet than the likes of you.” He grumbled.  His stare seemed to be daring her to do something, anything that would give him an excuse to call the guards on her.  So when two of them entered and sat down on the opposite end of the bar, she picked up her things and decided to go…quickly.<br>
<br>
The barkeep had apparently said something because no sooner had she left the place, she heard the clink clank of guard armor following close behind.  Without looking behind her, Wora picked up her pace.  The guards did the same.<br>
<br>
Where was Urda’s pup now?  She remembered with shame that she had told it to guard near the exit of the city.  Picking up into a run, she made her way back out to the city gates.<br>
<br>
The pup was there waiting for her where she left it.  When it saw what was coming behind her it bared its fangs and grimaced.  Wora motioned wildly with her hands.<br>
<br>
“No! No!  Just lead us out of here!”  The wolf stopped growling and started running alongside the city walls.  Wora followed.  From the sounds of it, the gate guards had joined in the chase.  She doubted they would wait for an explanation before they reached her.<br>
The wolf had come to a dead stop in front of a pedestal and was eyeing a book sitting on top.  Wora was dumbfounded.  She couldn’t hide behind a book!  Stupid dog!  But the dog just stared at it and Wora followed its gaze.<br>
<br>
There was a handprint on the open page.  Not front one hand but from the weight of many hands touching this one spot.  Touch the book?  Touch the book!<br>
<br>
She felt one of the guards grab her shoulder just as she placed her hand on the page.  She felt a strange pulling sensation as the world around her disappeared and was replaced by another place entirely.  It took Wora a moment to get her bearings.<br>
<br>
She was surrounded by green and gold and beauty everywhere she looked.  And people.  People of every race and size and color.  She grabbed the first halfling who would look at her and asked her where on earth she was.<br>
<br>
“Why, the Plane of Knowledge lass.”  The halfling looked up at her with round, concerned eyes.  “Are you ok?”<br>
<br>
Let’s see.  She hadn’t eaten for a few days.  She had been taunted by unreachable mead. And she had used the last of her energy to escape the Freeport guards.<br>
<br>
As Wora fell face first toward the floor, she managed to eek out, “Oh yeah.  Super.  Never felt better.”  And with a thunk, Wora was out cold.<br>
<br>
In the depths of the darkness, Wora could hear a voice say over the crowd around her.  “A barbarian?  Thunking her head on the cobblestones?  Gotta be a Pinesent…”<br>
